{"id":"2112.06338","submitter":"Yash Aggarwal","authors":"Yash Aggarwal","title":"Insights into the origins and growth of seeds of supermassive black\n  holes","comments":"26 pages, 4 figures, 4 tables","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.GA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  It is generally accepted that supermassive black holes (SMBHs) grew from\nprogenitor seeds; but it remains unclear when the seeds formed, how large they\nwere, and what were their growth rates. This study finds answers to such open\nquestions in an analysis and interpretation of available mass (MBH) and age (t)\ndata of SMBHs at z>5.7. Their distribution reveals that a significant number\n(36) spread over 300 million years (Myr) of cosmic time have markedly similar\nmasses (within a factor of 2) even though MBH depends on age. Besides age, MBH\ndepends upon seed mass Ms, origin time ts, and a variable dubbed accretion\nratio AR. The analysis leads to the conclusion that the 36 SMBHs had\nsimilar-size seeds that formed essentially concurrently and that AR is\ninversely proportional to t. Consequently, we get 36 equations with 1 variable\n(t) and 3 parameters. Solving these equations using the SANN method, the\noptimum values of the parameters define AR as a function of age t, and MBH as a\nfunction of Ms and t. These relationships are tested and applied to thousands\nof SMBHs. The results indicate that ts ~100Myr (z=30); that SMBHS > 1E+09M*\n(solar masses) require seeds > 1E+03M* but < 5E+04M*; that seeds grew at an\nexponentially increasing rate that reached a maximum near z=7 and decreased\nthereafter; that seeds may have initially experienced a short period (150 Myr)\nof super-Eddington accretion or accretion efficiency much <0.1; that about half\nof the growth occurs from z=30-3.5 and the rest thereafter, and that accretion\nis the predominant mode of growth with an upper limit of 2.2E+06Ms or\nMBH=(6.7+/-2)E+10M*. This study provides quantitative estimates of accretion\nrates, constraints for models of seed formation, and insights into the origins\nand growth of Sagittarius A*.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 12 Dec 2021 22:23:55 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 26 Jun 2022 19:29:31 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 28 Jul 2022 04:20:33 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Tue, 23 Aug 2022 03:22:37 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-08-24"}
